          "title": "God remembered Abraham — the theological hinge of the chapter (19:29)",
          "body": "Verse 29 is the chapter's interpretive master key, and its placement is deliberate. After the entire dramatic account of Lot's rescue — the angels, the urgency, the blindness, the seized hands, the fire — the narrator steps back and offers the theological explanation: 'God remembered Abraham, and sent Lot out of the midst of the overthrow.' Lot does not appear in this sentence as an agent. He is sent out. The credit goes entirely to God's memory of Abraham. The verb *zakhar* (remember) is the same verb used of God's remembrance of Noah in 8:1 at the height of the flood — a structural parallel the original reader would recognize. In both cases, a man is preserved inside global-scale divine judgment not because he earned it but because God remembered His covenant relationship with one who had gone before. This is, in miniature, the logic of substitutionary grace: Lot is rescued on the basis of another man's standing before God, not his own."
